Explore the behaviour of the algorithm both for TWO data sets which are linearly separable and for TWO datasets which are not linearly separable.¶

Done in Code

How dependent are the decision boundaries on the initial values of the weights? What do you see for each of the datasets when the initial weights are changed, and why?¶

If we initialize all weights with zeros then every hidden unit will get zero independent of the input. So, when all the hidden neurons have zero weights, then they get same gradient and updataion is also same, This only effects scale not direction. No matter what was the input - if all weights are the same, all units in hidden layer will be the same too.

Compare the final decision boundary in each of the above datasets against the decision boundary obtained using a SVM and logistic regression. What differences do you see and why?¶

Logistic Regression¶

It makes decision boundary based on logistic functions which is mainly probabilistic. While logistic regression the one that minimizes the cross-entropy loss.

SVM¶

SVM tries makes decision boundary that reduces the risk of error on the test data. It tries to find a decision boundary that has the same distance from the boundary points of both classes. Decision boundary has maximal margin from both classes. SVM is geometrically motivated rather than statistically.

Function to plot graph based on weight ans bais¶

In [2]:
def plotGraph(weight,bais,size,df,x):
    

    y = np.multiply((-weight[0]/weight[1]),x)-(bais/weight[1])

    colors = {-1:'red', 1:'blue'}
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    grouped = df.groupby('label')

    for key, group in grouped:
        group.plot(ax=ax, kind='scatter', x='x', y='y', label=key, color=colors[key])

    plt.plot(x,y)
    plt.show()

Perceptron algorithm¶

In [3]:
def perceptron(df,X,y,weight,bais,size=12,threshold=10):
    x  = np.random.randint(-10,10, size=(size))
    learning_rate = 0.01
    j = 0
    while(j!=threshold):
        j+=1
        for inputs,label in zip(X,y):
            yDash = np.dot(weight,inputs)+bais
            if yDash > 0:
                yDash = 1.0
            else:
                yDash = -1.0
            if yDash!=label:
                weight = weight + inputs*learning_rate*(label)
                bais = bais + learning_rate*(label)
        print("Iteration : ",j," Weights : ",weight, " bais : ",bais)
        plotGraph(weight,bais,size,df,x)
    return weight,bais
def predict(inputs,weight,bais):
    pred = np.dot(weight,inputs)+bais
    if pred <= 0:
        return 0
    else:
        return 1
